headline: GM Turns to the Magnificent Seven to Compete With Tesla
summary: General Motors  shares hit a record high on Tuesday after the company’s better-than-expected third-quarter earnings report.  The move came after shares rose 15% on Tuesday, closing at a record $66.62, according to Dow Jones Market Data.  GM emerged from bankruptcy protection in 2009 and shares began trading again in 2010.

headline: Why xAI Is Still a Wild Card
summary: While investors may view Tesla as an artificial intelligence play these days, they shouldn’t forget CEO Elon Musk’s other AI business, xAI.  Earlier on Wednesday, General Motors unveiled plans for self-driving cars and natural language AI chatbots, all of which will be designed to enhance future products.  AI applications, the computers to train them, and powerful onboard computers will be needed to win in the car business of the future.

headline: Which Auto Makers Could Follow GM’s Rally? A Look at the Charts Ahead of Tesla Earnings.
summary: General Motors  delivered a blowout earnings report yesterday, offering a jolt of optimism to the auto sector.  The company posted results well ahead of expectations, driven by resilient demand, strong pricing, and disciplined cost control, perhaps setting the tone for legacy auto makers heading into year end.  GM’s rally came with enormous volume, likely catching shorts off guard and attracting new longs, a potent combination.

headline: Early US Earnings Point to Best Corporate Results in Four Years
summary: About 85% of S&P 500 firms to have reported third-quarter earnings so far have surpassed profit estimates, on course for the best performance since 2021, according to data compiled by Bloomberg Intelligence.  It’s still early in the season, given that less than a fifth of the index’s market capitalization has announced results, but it’s an indication that US profits remain strong in the face of tariffs and an uncertain economy.  A majority of S&P 500 firms typically surpass expectations, but this season stands out considering that analysts had set the bar higher by raising projections heading into the reporting period.
